TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Equilibrium Model of Management Group Performance
AU  - Crouch, Andrew
Y1  - 1987/07/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1987.4306564
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1987.4306564
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 499
EP  - 510
VL  - 12
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - An equilibrium model is developed to explain persisting performances of managers and subordinates in management groups. The influence subordinates have in solving unstructured problems is advanced as a factor which discriminates between groups that perform above average and those that do not. The model predicts that over time management groups respond to exogenous disturbances by changing to either a stable high or low performance configuration.
AB  - An equilibrium model is developed to explain persisting performances of managers and subordinates in management groups. The influence subordinates have in solving unstructured problems is advanced as a factor which discriminates between groups that perform above average and those that do not. The model predicts that over time management groups respond to exogenous disturbances by changing to either a stable high or low performance configuration.
